  "pride_metadata": {
    "project": {
      "accession": "PXD052939",
      "title": "Structural mechanism of \u03b3-carboxylation coupled to vitamin K epoxidation at membrane interface",
      "additionalAttributes": [],
      "projectDescription": "Hemostasis and various non-hemostatic physiologies require \u03b3-carboxylation of designated glutamates in vitamin K-dependent proteins (VKDPs), a process coupled with epoxidation of vitamin K hydroquinone (KH2) by membrane-integrated \u03b3-carboxylase (VKGC). To understand this unique biochemistry, we determined cryo-electron microscopy structures of human VKGC in unbound form, with KH2 and four VKDPs possessing propeptides and glutamate-rich domains in different carboxylation states. VKGC recognizes propeptides via knob-and-hole interactions and adaptively binds tethered glutamate-containing segments. Propeptide binding allosterically triggers KH2 epoxidation, from which successive reactions generate a hydroxide superbase that deprotonates \u03b3-carbon of a glutamate positioned by hydrogen bonding. A sealed hydrophobic tunnel protects and guides superbase diffusion to reach this carboxylation site across membrane interface. These structural insights and functional findings advance membrane enzymology and inspire anticoagulation therapies.",
      "sampleProcessingProtocol": "Mass spectrometry detection of \u03b3-carboxylation  HEK293S GnTI- cells expressing the TMG2-Bril-VKGC fusion protein were grown in Freestyle medium containing 10 \u00b5M warfarin to block endogenous \u03b3-carboxylation. After protein purification, in vitro \u03b3-carboxylation was carried out in a 125 uL reaction mixture containing 20 ug TMG2-Bril-VKGC protein, 1.47 mM NaH13CO3, 222 uM KH2, 0.16% POPC, 0.16% CHAPS, 500 mM NaCl, and 25 mM MOPS, pH 7.5 at 25\u2103 for 4 h. After quenching the reaction with 10 \u00b5L of 10 M NaOH, the samples were processed using a filter aided sample preparation method. Briefly, Microcon centrifugal filters (Millipore Sigma, 30 kDa cutoff) were pre-rinsed with 100 mM [NH4]HCO3 via centrifugation, after which 200 \u00b5L of 8 M urea and the samples were added and gently mixed. The mixture was centrifuged at 10,000g for 30 min at 4\u00b0C, followed by three washes with urea through repeated centrifugation. The denatured protein was reduced by incubation with 100 \u00b5L of 50 mM tris(2-carboxyethyl)phosphine (TCEP) at room temperature, 37 \u00b0C for 30 min, and then alkylated with 100 \u00b5L of 100 mM iodoacetamide (IAA) at room temperature in the dark for 30 min.  The mixtures were centrifuged at 12,000g for 30 min at 4\u00b0C, followed by three washes with 100 \u00b5L of 100 mM [NH4]HCO3 through repeated centrifugation. Subseqently, the samples were digested with 1 \u00b5g trypsin in 50 \u00b5L of 100 mM [NH4]HCO3 and 0.05% ProteaseMax for 14 h in a 37\u00b0C water bath. Tryptic peptides were collected through centrifugation at 12,000g for 30 min, with another wash of 50 \u00b5L 100 mM [NH4]HCO3 to retrieve the remnants. The peptides were diluted to a concentration of ~0.1 mg/mL with 1% formic acid (FA), 2% acetonitrile (ACN) in H2O, for subsequent MS analyses.   For the detection of \u03b3-carboxylated FIX produced in cells, HEK293S GnTI- cells expressing the FIX-Bril-VKGC fusion protein were cultured for 3 d in Freestyle medium with 10 \u00b5M warfarin to inhibit endogenous \u03b3-carboxylation or with 20 \u03bcM vitamin K to promote \u03b3-carboxylation. Subsequently, the fusion protein was purified and samples for MS analyses were prepared as described above. The samples were analyzed by online nanoflow liquid chromatography tandem mass spectrometry (LC-MS/MS) using either electron-transfer dissociation (ETD) or higher energy collisional dissociation (HCD) fragmentation.  The ETD experiments used an Orbitrap Ascend Tribrid Mass Spectrometer (ThermoFisher Scientific, San Jose, CA) with a Nanospray Flex source (ThermoFisher Scientific, San Jose, CA) coupled online to an Vanquish Neo UHPLC System (ThermoFisher Scientific, San Jose, CA). Samples of 2 \u00b5L, containing ~200 ng peptides, were loaded onto an Easy-Spray\u2122 PepMap\u2122 Neo 2 \u03bcm C18, 75 \u03bcm \u00d7 150 mm microcapillary column. Analysis was performed at room temperature using a 110-minute MS method at a flow rate of 0.300 \u00b5L/min with the following gradient profile: (min:%B) 0:0; 95:30; 105:45; 105.5:95; 110:95. The Orbitrap Ascend Tribrid Mass Spectrometer was operated in data-dependent positive ion mode acquiring ETD MS/MS scans after each MS1 scan (resolution = 120,000, standard AGC target) on the most abundant ions using an intensity threshold of 1 \u00d7 104. The maximum injection time utilized for MS/MS scans was 100 ms using the ion trap, with ion trap scan rate set to rapid and a first mass of 110 m/z.  The dynamic exclusion time was set to 6 s, with the isotope exclusion function enabled. Charge inclusion was enabled for charge states 2-5 with mass range of 300-950 m/z, and charge states 6-8.   For HCD analyses, a NanoElute 2 (Bruker Daltonics, Germany) UHPLC nano-flow system was coupled online to timsTOF Pro2 mass spectrometer (Bruker Daltonics, Germany) with a nano-electrospray ion source with CaptiveSpray ZDV Sprayer (Bruker Daltonics, Germany). Samples were injected and online desalted using a trap cartridge (Thermo Scientific PepMap Neo Trap Cartridge). Liquid chromatography was performed at 40 \u00b0C and on a PepSep C18 column (15 cm length \u00d7 150 \u03bcm i.d., 1.5 \u03bcm particle size) (Bruker Daltonics, Germany). The HPLC solvent A was 0.1% FA in H2O, and solvent B was 0.1% FA in 100% ACN. Samples were analyzed using a 70 min MS method at a flow rate of 400nL/min with the following gradient profile: (min:%B) 0:2; 35:20; 50:36; 60:95; 110; 95. The timsTOF Pro 2 was operated in PASEF mode (103, 104). Mass spectra for MS and MS/MS scans were recorded between 100 and 1700 m/z. Ion mobility resolution was set to 0.60\u20131.60 V\u00b7s/cm over a ramp time of 100 ms. Data-dependent acquisition was performed using 10 PASEF MS/MS scans per cycle with a near 100% duty cycle. A polygon filter was applied in the m/z and ion mobility space to exclude low m/z, non-peptide singly charged ions from PASEF precursor selection. An active exclusion time of 0.4 min was applied to precursors that reached 20,000 intensity units. Collisional energy was ramped stepwise as a function of ion mobility.",
      "dataProcessingProtocol": "Samples were analyzed using PMI Byos PTM workflow (v5.5.39 x64).  The following parameters were used to analyze ETD FIX samples: FIX and VKGC sequences (sourced from uniProt), 10ppm precursor tolerance, ETD fragmentation, 0.2Da fragment tolerance, C-terminal fully specific cleavage at arginine and lysine residues, 1 missed cleavage, 10,000 max precursor charge, 1% FDR, and the following modifications (allowing for 4 common and 2 rare): Oxidation (rare1, +15.994915 @ M, W), Carboxylation (common3, +43.989829 @ E), and carbamidomethylation (fixed, +57.021464 @ C).  For TMG2 samples, a similar workflow was used but the modification \u03b3-carboxylation (common6, +44.99318 @ E) was added and the FIX sequence was replaced with that of TMG2 (uniProt).  For HCD samples, the same parameters were used but with HCD fragmentation and a precursor mass tolerance of 20ppm.",
      "projectTags": [],
